<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN, INDIA FORGE TIES TO BOOST TECHNOLOGICAL EXCHANGES
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New  Delhi,  April  18 (CNA) 04/18/07  21:47:52 (By Paul Kuo and
Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
<P>
The Republic of China signed a memorandum of understanding with
India Wednesday on cooperation in the fields of science and
technology, sources at the Taipei Economic and Cultural Center
(TECC), the ROC's representative office in India, said that day.
</P>
<P>
The two parties agreed in the accord to promote bilateral
cooperation in the fields of nanotechnology, semiconductors,
aviation and space, satellite development, biotechnology and
agriculture, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The new ties will also facilitate other forms of collaboration
between  the  two sides,  such  as  programs  to  encourage
commercialization  of  research  and development,  sustainable
development and innovation.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held in Taipei with ROC Representative to India
Kao Chen-chun and his Indian counterpart T.P. Seetharam signing
the memorandum. Chen Chien-jen, minister of Taiwan's National
Science Council (NSC), attended the event.
</P>
<P>
According to the memorandum, the NSC and India's Cabinet-level
Department of Science and Technology will establish a joint
committee for work including scientific talent exchanges and the
promotion of joint technological development projects.
</P>
<P>
Chang Ho-chung, chief of the TECC technology division, said the
two sides have long had interest in forging cooperative relations
and have organized many workshops for cooperative proposals in
the fields of genetic research and biochemistry.  An Indian
official in charge of science and technology affairs who
requested anonymity confirmed the signing, saying that the
cooperation is only aimed at enhancing the promotion of
technological development and mutual bilateral exchanges.
</P>
